Processing scRNA-Seq Data with Seurat

Introduction

This is a brief tutorial on working with single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-seq) data in Seurat. The primary dataset used here contains hematopoietic populations from the bone marrow of AML patients and healthy controls (van Galen et al.2019). The data is available in GEO under accession GSE116256.

Load packages

Load the relevant packages (tidyverse for general data manipulation, Seurat for scRNA-seq analysis, and ggsci for pleasant color schemes).

library(tidyverse)
library(Seurat)
library(ggsci)

Import data

Import the expression matrix for sample AML329-D0. The read_tsv() function from the readr package (part of tidyverse) can download data from both local and remote sources.

AML329_dem_tbl <- read_tsv("https://ftp.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/samples/GSM3587nnn/GSM3587940/suppl/GSM3587940_AML329-D0.dem.txt.gz", show_col_types = FALSE)
dim(AML329_dem_tbl)
[1] 27899   526
AML329_dem_tbl[1:8, 1:8]

Import the annotations table for sample AML329-D0.

AML329_annot_tbl <- read_tsv("https://ftp.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/samples/GSM3587nnn/GSM3587941/suppl/GSM3587941_AML329-D0.anno.txt.gz", show_col_types = FALSE)
dim(AML329_annot_tbl)
[1] 525  28
head(AML329_annot_tbl)

Clean up data

By default, read_tsv() will create a tibble (data.frames that are lazy and surly).

class(AML329_dem_tbl)
[1] "spec_tbl_df" "tbl_df"      "tbl"         "data.frame"

The expression data should be a matrix with genes as rows and cells as columns.

AML329_dem_mat <- AML329_dem_tbl %>%

Create the Seurat object

Initialize the Seurat object from the raw counts matrix.

AML329_so <- CreateSeuratObject(counts = AML329_dem_mat, min.cells = 1, min.features = 1)
Warning: Feature names cannot have underscores ('_'), replacing with dashes ('-')Warning: Feature names cannot have underscores ('_'), replacing with dashes ('-')
AML329_so
An object of class Seurat 
15909 features across 525 samples within 1 assay 
Active assay: RNA (15909 features, 0 variable features)
 2 layers present: counts, data

By default, all the data is stored in the RNA assay.

AML329_so@assays
$RNA
Assay data with 15909 features for 525 cells
First 10 features:
 A1BG, A1BG-AS1, A2M, A2M-AS1, A2ML1, A2MP1, A4GALT, AAAS, AACS, AADAT

The [[ operator can add columns to object metadata. We can add the percentage of reads that map to the mitochondrial genome.

AML329_so[["pct_mito"]] <- PercentageFeatureSet(AML329_so, pattern = "^MT-")

The metadata is stored as a data frame in the meta.data slot.

head(AML329_so@meta.data)

We can add additional metadata using AddMetaData().

AML329_so <- AddMetaData(AML329_so, metadata = AML329_anno_df)
head(AML329_so@meta.data)

These cells are already pre-filtered, but we can visualize the QC metrics anyway.

VlnPlot(AML329_so, features = c("nFeature_RNA", "nCount_RNA", "pct_mito"), ncol = 3)

Perform standard analysis (log-transformed)

The default global-scaling normalization method LogNormalize normalizes the feature expression measurements for each cell by the total expression, multiplies by a scale factor of 10,000, and log-transforms the result.

AML329_so <- NormalizeData(AML329_so, normalization.method = "LogNormalize")
Performing log-normalization

Identify highly variable features, scale, and perform dimensionality reduction.

AML329_so <- FindVariableFeatures(AML329_so, verbose = FALSE)
AML329_so <- ScaleData(AML329_so, vars.to.regress = "pct_mito", verbose = FALSE)
AML329_so <- RunPCA(AML329_so, verbose = FALSE)
# AML329_so <- FindNeighbors(AML329_so)
# AML329_so <- FindClusters(AML329_so, resolution = c(0.8, 1, 1.2))
AML329_so <- RunUMAP(AML329_so, dims = 1:30, verbose = FALSE)

To use Python UMAP via reticulate, set umap.method to 'umap-learn' and metric to 'correlation'

Generate UMAPs

Define the color gradient colors (from light gray to dark red).

gradient_colors <- c("gray90", "red4")

Check some known population marker genes.

FeaturePlot(AML329_so, reduction = "umap", features = "CD34", cols = gradient_colors) +
  theme(aspect.ratio = 1)

FeaturePlot(AML329_so, reduction = "umap", features = "MPO", cols = gradient_colors) +
  theme(aspect.ratio = 1)

Check the metadata overlaid onto the UMAP.

FeaturePlot(AML329_so, reduction = "umap", features = "Score_HSC", cols = gradient_colors) +
  theme(aspect.ratio = 1)

DimPlot(AML329_so, reduction = "umap", group.by = "CellType", shuffle = TRUE) +
  theme(aspect.ratio = 1) +
  scale_color_igv()

DimPlot(AML329_so, reduction = "umap", group.by = "PredictionRefined", shuffle = TRUE) +
  theme(aspect.ratio = 1) +
  scale_color_igv()

Perform sctransform-based analysis

Run sctransform.

AML329_so <- SCTransform(AML329_so, vars.to.regress = "pct_mito", verbose = FALSE)

The sctransform results are stored in the new SCT assay.

AML329_so@assays

Perform dimensionality reduction based on the new sctransform normalization.

AML329_so <- RunPCA(AML329_so, verbose = FALSE)
AML329_so <- RunUMAP(AML329_so, dims = 1:30, verbose = FALSE)

Get cluster markers (differentially expressed genes)

Set the assay to prevent any potential confusion later.

DefaultAssay(AML329_so) <- "RNA"

Set the cell identities to a specific grouping.

Idents(AML329_so) <- "CellType"
table(Idents(AML329_so))

         GMP     GMP-like    Prog-like            T         Mono          CTL 
          13          134           67           80           33            8 
    HSC-like      ProMono      lateEry         Prog     cDC-like ProMono-like 
           9            8           45           13           25            7 
   Mono-like           NK          cDC     earlyEry            B          HSC 
          11           29           12            7           16            2 
      Plasma          pDC 
           4            2

Find markers for every cluster compared to all remaining cells. There are many parameters you can adjust to make the process more or less stringent.

AML329_markers <- FindAllMarkers(AML329_so, only.pos = TRUE, min.pct = 0.2, test.use = "wilcox", logfc.threshold = 0.2, min.cells.group = 10, verbose = FALSE)

Check the top markers for each cluster (or cell type in this example). Some of the cell types will be missing in the output since they have too few cells.

AML329_markers %>%
  group_by(cluster) %>%
  slice_max(n = 5, order_by = avg_log2FC)
